aspace_helpers.title: modify Princeton_EAD_Exporter plugin to export component uri's

comments.body:
Atlassian wiki on modifying the exporter:
https://archivesspace.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/ADC/blog/2015/03/15/18088140/Customizing+your+ArchivesSpace+EAD+importers+and+exporters.

Nice concise example for a container plugin (Yale):
https://github.com/archivesspace-labs/yale-ead-exporter/blob/master/backend/model/yale_ead_exporter.rb

This bit in serialize-child seems like a candidate for modification:
https://github.com/archivesspace/archivesspace/blob/master/backend/app/exporters/serializers/ead.rb#L310-312

And this bit in stream?
https://github.com/archivesspace/archivesspace/blob/master/backend/app/exporters/serializers/ead.rb#L186-192

We found that when going to a show page for a record which is in two different exhibits, the solr record that's being rendered might not be the correct one.

For example, https://dpul.princeton.edu/happy_gall-entines_day/catalog/nz8060449 should come from the happy_gall-entines_day exhibit, but it's the one from PUDL0017 (you can tell by going to `/raw` and looking at the exhibit prefix..

Is the solr record that is rendered dictated by what DPUL collection was created first with that item (like your example link)? or is it random? we have items with multiple collection tags in figgy. I wonder what the consequences are?
A solr record is generated for each unique collection / resource pair. We need to fix the code to pull the right record.

dspace-development.title: Ensure that the Elements citation API endpoints have OIT firewall rules created to permit outbound requests

comments.body: I have attempted several of the solutions within the  https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/mem/configmgr/core/plan-design/security/enable-tls-1-2-troubleshoot. I am afraid that I shall need to advance this with OIT. Please find the SN@P ticket at the following: https://princeton.service-now.com/service?id=ticket&sys_id=894d4d8287ed09149cd197183cbb35e2&table=incident

The OIT systems infrastructure manager has just clarified that the URL endpoints for *all* of the citation data endpoints which are queried must have firewall exceptions created. Currently, the TLS 1.2 is properly enabled for these servers.

Immediately, I can identify that the server must be permitted to request the following URLs:

- [ ] https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/efetch.fcgi
- [ ] https://www.ebi.ac.uk/europepmc/webservices/rest/search/query
This is now in progress with https://princeton.service-now.com/service?id=ticket&table=sc_req_item&sys_id=d16edd9e87a54d149cd197183cbb3546&view=sp
The firewall rules are reported to be in place, hence, this may *not* be related to the firewall, or some other cause might be triggering this error.

Attempting to modify some of the configuration locally within the PowerShell does seem to be somewhat effective:

```pwsh

PS C:\windows\system32> [Net.ServicePointManager]::SecurityProtocol = [Enum]::ToObject([Net.SecurityProtocolType], 3072)

PS C:\windows\system32> $Response = Invoke-WebRequest -Uri "https://google.com"

PS C:\windows\system32> $Response 


StatusCode        : 200
```

Yet, this still does not prove to be a solution for the necessary URLs:

```posh

PS C:\windows\system32> [Net.ServicePointManager]::SecurityProtocol = [Net.SecurityProtocolType]::Tls, [Net.SecurityProtocolType]::Tls11, [Net.SecurityProtocolType]::Tls12, [Net.SecurityProtocolType]::Ssl3

PS C:\windows\system32> [Net.ServicePointManager]::SecurityProtocol = "Tls, Tls11, Tls12, Ssl3"

PS C:\windows\system32> $uri
https://eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/entrez/eutils/efetch.fcgi

PS C:\windows\system32>  $Response = Invoke-WebRequest -Uri $uri
Invoke-WebRequest : The request was aborted: Could not create SSL/TLS secure channel.
At line:1 char:14 

```
